<Post title="Distributed Training Over a Laptop Fleet" date="April 2026" activeTab="deep-dive">
  <p>
    Training on a single game instance is painfully slow — each combat takes 10-30
    seconds of real time. To get enough episodes for PPO to converge, I needed to
    parallelize across multiple machines.
  </p>

  <h2>The Architecture</h2>
  <p>
    The system uses an actor-learner split. One machine runs the learner (PPO training
    loop). Multiple worker machines each run several headless game instances connected
    to a local actor proxy. The actor proxies do local inference with a copy of the
    policy and push completed episodes to the learner over TCP.
  </p>

  <h2>Weight Synchronization</h2>
  <p>
    Every 16 episodes, each actor proxy pulls fresh weights from the learner. The
    learner serializes the full state dict (including vocab mappings) and sends it
    over the socket. The actor proxy loads the new weights, resizes embeddings if
    the vocabulary grew, and continues.
  </p>

  <h2>Challenges</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Flaky LAN connections</strong> — Workers drop and reconnect. The protocol handles this with automatic retry and reconnect logic.</li>
    <li><strong>Stale weights</strong> — Workers running old weights produce off-policy data. The 16-episode pull interval balances freshness vs overhead.</li>
    <li><strong>Remote deployment</strong> — Getting game instances started on remote machines over SSH on Windows required creative workarounds (scheduled tasks as a process detachment mechanism).</li>
    <li><strong>Device Guard</strong> — Some worker machines block the game executable via Windows security policies, requiring per-machine troubleshooting.</li>
  </ul>

